   "source": [
    "### Stacking and Exporting Arrays\n",
    "\n",
    "Oftentimes, we want to export multiple 1D arrays to a commonly readable file, such as `.csv`. Numpy has a few methods supporting this, but with some caveats:\n",
    "- Multiple arrays can be stacked into columns or rows, particularly useful for 1D data\n",
    "- Stacking and exporting require the arrays to have the **same shape** and **same data type**\n",
    "\n",
    "This is often sufficient for simple cases, but it can suffer in terms of user readability because numerical columns cannot easily have string headers. [Pandas DataFrames](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/frame.html), which has its own [lesson](Pandas.ipynb), has more robust handling for these situations; however, stacking and exporting Numpy arrays is typically more user-friendly than DataFrames, which is why we will cover both cases."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "e171aa89-7dd2-4560-9ea2-de89c7fbcd30",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "time = np.linspace(0, 1, num = 1000)\n",
    "flux = np.random.rand(len(time))/10 + 0.95\n",
    "flux[200:300] = flux[200:300] - 0.2\n",
    "error = np.ones(len(flux))*0.05\n",
    "plt.ylim(0, 1.4)\n",
    "plt.errorbar(time, flux, yerr=error)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "c6338366-77ec-4d7a-be9a-cf1c127412e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To export our data as a 3-column `.csv`, we would need to use `np.vstack` on all three of our 1D arrays, **transpose**, then pass `np.savetext` delimited by a comma."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "aa261e5a-9242-495f-adb5-7960fca3686e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#Note the double parentheses! vstack takes a tuple of arrays as its argument. Also note the transpose! \n",
    "# vstack as it is will save each data frame as a row, so transposing makes each array a column\n",
    "X = np.vstack((time, flux, error)).T\n",
    "#The first argument is the directory and file name. As it is now, it will save the file in the current directory\n",
    "np.savetxt(\"Data.csv\", X, delimiter=',')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0ccd153e-e743-4a58-8964-5db4e5bc959d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
